{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19190"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19190"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.19,0.04,0.26,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81937"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11924"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67207"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"8785"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81937"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-week gestation infant is admitted to the neonatal intensive care unit. She weighs 780 grams at birth and requires mechanical ventilation and supplemental oxygen. She has no other medical conditions and takes no regular medications. At six weeks of age, routine eye examination reveals a demarcation line between vascularised and avascular retina in zone II of both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical vitrectomy","Immediate laser photocoagulation","Discharge from ophthalmology follow-up","Anti-VEGF injection","Weekly ophthalmology review"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes stage 1 retinopathy of prematurity (ROP) in a very premature infant. The demarcation line between vascularised and avascular retina is the earliest manifestation of ROP. At this stage, the condition may either resolve spontaneously or progress to more severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeekly ophthalmology review\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management at this stage. Close monitoring is essential to detect any progression to more advanced stages that would require intervention. The frequency of examinations may be adjusted based on the findings and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate laser photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for type 1 ROP (zone I, any stage with plus disease; zone I, stage 3 without plus disease; or zone II, stage 2 or 3 with plus disease). This patient\u0027s findings are too mild to warrant laser treatment at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-VEGF injection\u003C/strong\u003E is an emerging treatment option for severe ROP, particularly in zone I disease. However, it is not indicated for stage 1 disease where observation is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical vitrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be considered in advanced stages with retinal detachment (stages 4 or 5). This patient has early-stage disease that does not require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge from ophthalmology follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this infant requires ongoing monitoring until the retina is fully vascularised or the condition resolves. Premature discontinuation of screening could miss progression to vision-threatening disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinopathy of prematurity primarily affects premature infants with lower gestational age and birthweight carrying higher risk.","The pathogenesis involves abnormal retinal vascular development with VEGF playing a key role in neovascularization.","Regular screening of at-risk premature infants is essential for early detection and management of ROP."],"references":["Kliegman RM, St. Geme JW, Blum NJ, Shah SS, Tasker RC, Wilson KM, editors. Retinopathy of prematurity. In: Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 21st ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19190"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T13:31:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T13:32:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11924"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81937"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"hea